he first known bearer of the epithet was Domhnall Caomhánach (Donal Kavanagh, died in 1175), the son of Diarmait Mac Murchadha (Dermot McMurrough), king of Leinster in the 12th century. Despite being killed at an early age, Domhnall Caomhánach gave his name to a large and important family in Irish history."],"variants":[{"name":"Kinsella","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Ciaran, Donal, Finbar, Fintan.","Irish (Wexford and Carlow): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Cinnsealach</b>, or occasionally <b>Ó Cinnsealaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Cinnsealach</i>’, an adjectival personal name meaning ‘proud, masterful’ or ‘chief warrior’. <i>Cinnsealach</i> can also indicate a member of the older population grouping called <i>Uí Chinnsealaigh</i>; compare the origin of   Kavanagh  ."]},{"name":"Kevin","meanings":["Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Caoimhín</b> ‘descendant of <i>Caoimhín</i>’ (the personal name <i>Kevin</i>), a name derived from <i>Caémgein</i> ‘comely birth’ although now regarded as a diminutive of Gaelic <i>caomh</i> ‘comely, beloved’. Compare   Kavanagh  ."]},{"name":"Cavanaugh","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Brennan, Aileen, Dermod, Donal, Patrick Sean.","Irish: variant of   Kavanagh  ."]},{"name":"Cavanah","meanings":["with stress on the first syllable, this is a shortened Anglicized form of <b>Mac Caomhánach</b>, see   Kavanagh  .","alternatively, with stress on <i>-van-</i>, this is a shortened form of <b>McCavana</b>, from <b>Mac an Mhanaigh</b>, ‘son of the monk’ (from <i>manach</i> ‘monk’). This was a Mayo surname, also Anglicized by translation as   Monk   and   Monks  .","Irish:"]},{"name":"Cavender","meanings":["English: most probably a nickname from an Anglo-Norman French equivalent of French <i>chavender</i> ‘chub’ (the fish).","English (of Irish origin): Anglicized form of   Kavanagh   (and its variants, including <b>Cavenagh</b>) or   Cavanna  . Compare   Cavinder  .","History: Hugh Cavenagh (died <i>c.</i> 1709) came from Bristol in England to Westmoreland County, VA, in 1658 as an indentured servant for a five-year period to a Mr. Wills. His descendants spell their name mainly <i>Cavender</i> and <i>Cavinder</i>."]},{"name":"Kaveney","meanings":["Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Géibheannaigh</b> or <b>Mac Géibheannaigh</b>, ‘descendant or son of <i>Géibheannach</i>’, a personal name based on <i>géibheannach</i> meaning ‘bound, or captive one’. There may have been some confusion between this name and   Kavanagh  ."]},{"name":"Cavanagh","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Brennan, Fergus.","Irish: variant of   Kavanagh  ."]},{"name":"Kavanaugh","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Oonagh.","Irish: variant of   Kavanagh  ."]}]},{"name":"Domhnall","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Gaelic: from Old Celtic <i>dubno</i> ‘world’ + <i>val</i> ‘rule’.  See also  <b>Donald</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1355923,"age":2,"year":"1167","julianDay":2147298,"description":"Arrival of Normans at Baginbun in Co. Wexford thus started 800 year struggle between English and Irish.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Domhnall Kavanagh was born in 1165, in Ireland as the son of Domhnall Caomhánach Mac Murchada, King of Leinster. He had at least 3 sons with Kavanagh."},"et":{"1165–":"1165–Surnud","1165–Male":"1165–Surnud","1197–Male":"1197–Surnud","1190–Female":"1190–Surnud","1204–1323":"1204–1323","1209–1282":"1209–1282","1215–1281":"1215–1281","1140–1175":"1140–1175","1190":"1190","1165":"1165","1175":"1175","1197":"1197","ABT 1215":"umbes 1215","1140":"1140","1282":"1282","1281":"1281","1204":"1204","1215":"1215","1323":"1323","1167":"1167","1209":"1209","Leinster Province, Ireland":"Leinster, Iirimaa","Ireland":"Iirimaa"},"fi":{"1165–":"1165–Kuollut","1165–Male":"1165–Kuollut","1197–Male":"1197–Kuollut","1190–Fem